long_description:
Kepler-11 is the fullestCOMMA most compact planetary system yet discovered beyond our own. NASA's Kepler space telescope discovered six planets made of a mix of rock and gases orbiting a yellow dwarf starCOMMA located approximately 2COMMA000 light-years from Earth. The orbits of the five inner planets in the Kepler-11 planetary system are much closer together than any of the planets in our solar system. If placed inside our solar systemCOMMA Kepler-11g would orbit between Mercury and VenusCOMMA and the other five planets would orbit between Mercury and our sun. The innermost planetCOMMA Kepler-11bCOMMA is 10 times closer to its star than Earth is to the sun. All six planets are larger than EarthCOMMA with the largest comparable in size to Uranus and Neptune.

long_description:
TRAPPIST-1d is one of seven Earth-sized planets in the TRAPPIST-1 system. About 40 light-years from EarthCOMMA TRAPPIST-1 is unusual both for its number of small rocky planets and the number in the habitable zone. Several of the artist's illustrations shown above portray possible water or ice in the system– the proximity of the planets to their red dwarf star may indicate that any of them could have water on their surface. This artist's concept shows TRAPPIST-1d with a narrow band of water near the terminatorCOMMA the divide between a hotCOMMA dry day and an ice-covered night side.
